00:01:40.260 --> 00:01:42.450
"Can you speak on
the possibility

00:01:42.450 --> 00:01:44.380
of a dystopian singularity?

00:01:44.380 --> 00:01:47.460
What are the potential
threats of a Utopian future?"

00:01:47.460 --> 00:01:47.960
Sure.

00:01:47.960 --> 00:01:50.810
Look, I think Kurzweil has
talked about this a lot

00:01:50.810 --> 00:01:51.580
as well.

00:01:51.580 --> 00:01:54.020
Technology has always
been a double-edged sword.

00:01:54.020 --> 00:01:56.730
Technology extends
our reach, but it

00:01:56.730 --> 00:01:58.920
can extend our reach
in any direction.

00:01:58.920 --> 00:02:03.660
Perhaps the man that discovered
fire, as Kurzweil says,

00:02:03.660 --> 00:02:06.409
was probably burned at the
stake by his contemporaries.

00:02:06.409 --> 00:02:07.950
So we can use fire
to cook our foods,

00:02:07.950 --> 00:02:10.690
or we can use fire
to burn one another.

00:02:10.690 --> 00:02:12.830
So we use these tools,
we use these instruments,

00:02:12.830 --> 00:02:16.550
to extend the boundaries of
our thought, of our reach,

00:02:16.550 --> 00:02:19.280
of our vision, to
extend ourselves.

00:02:19.280 --> 00:02:21.030
But it's how we choose
to extend ourselves

00:02:21.030 --> 00:02:23.238
that ultimately determines
the effect that technology

00:02:23.238 --> 00:02:24.491
has on our future.

00:02:24.491 --> 00:02:26.490
And I think that's where
cultural narratives are

00:02:26.490 --> 00:02:27.100
important.

00:02:27.100 --> 00:02:28.620
That's where memes
are important.

00:02:28.620 --> 00:02:33.680
That's where, again, these
narratives that will ultimately

00:02:33.680 --> 00:02:35.880
inform how we use these
tools are crucial.

00:02:35.880 --> 00:02:38.510
So that's what publishing
platforms like TED

00:02:38.510 --> 00:02:39.530
are so important.

00:02:39.530 --> 00:02:42.250
That's why I make my videos,
to put them out there,

00:02:42.250 --> 00:02:45.320
to inspire a greater
vision of life, a greater

00:02:45.320 --> 00:02:46.630
vision of what's possible.

00:02:46.630 --> 00:02:49.230
But if you actually
map out human progress

00:02:49.230 --> 00:02:52.730
over the last 100 years,
contrary to popular belief,

00:02:52.730 --> 00:02:56.080
we have to used these
tools to make life better.

00:02:56.080 --> 00:02:58.232
Steven Pinker's work
talks about the fact

00:02:58.232 --> 00:03:00.690
that the chances of a man dying
at the hands of another man

00:03:00.690 --> 00:03:02.990
today are the lowest
than they've ever been.

00:03:02.990 --> 00:03:05.630
The world has actually never
been less violent than it is

00:03:05.630 --> 00:03:08.380
today, contrary
to popular belief.

00:03:08.380 --> 00:03:11.290
So it's not utopia yet,
but it's leaning that way,

00:03:11.290 --> 00:03:14.590
as Steven Johnson likes to say.

00:03:14.590 --> 00:03:16.660
More questions.

00:03:16.660 --> 00:03:17.160
Let's see.

00:03:20.800 --> 00:03:24.080
"What are the actions you can
take beyond reading and talking

00:03:24.080 --> 00:03:29.790
about this kind of
awesome vision?"

00:03:29.790 --> 00:03:36.170
Well, I think use the
tools at your disposal

00:03:36.170 --> 00:03:41.030
to basically put out your unique
vision, add it to the world.

00:03:41.030 --> 00:03:43.130
We've never had such
tools with which

00:03:43.130 --> 00:03:47.440
to create ripples
that can transform.

00:03:47.440 --> 00:03:49.440
It's this idea that a
young person with a cell

00:03:49.440 --> 00:03:51.990
phone in Africa today
has better communications

00:03:51.990 --> 00:03:54.400
technology in the US
president had 25 years ago.

00:03:54.400 --> 00:03:57.520
So how might this young
child use this tool?

00:03:57.520 --> 00:04:00.330
How might he use it to
extend his creativity?

00:04:00.330 --> 00:04:04.420
To remix his fear
of possibilities?

00:04:04.420 --> 00:04:06.170
It's not my job, I
think, to tell you

00:04:06.170 --> 00:04:08.100
how or what you can do.

00:04:08.100 --> 00:04:11.410
It's mostly just to inspire
you to believe that you can.

00:04:11.410 --> 00:04:13.220
But I think you have
to ultimately discover

00:04:13.220 --> 00:04:14.890
your own path.

00:04:14.890 --> 00:04:17.500
What is your
contribution going to be?

00:04:17.500 --> 00:04:20.570
That, I think, is the question
we can all ask ourselves.

00:04:20.570 --> 00:04:23.720
In fact, at Singularity
University in Silicon Valley,

00:04:23.720 --> 00:04:27.350
they've created this whole
university at the NASA Ames

00:04:27.350 --> 00:04:28.966
campus to encourage
and teach people

00:04:28.966 --> 00:04:30.840
to think exponentially
about what's possible.

00:04:30.840 --> 00:04:33.720
The idea is that passionate
individuals today

00:04:33.720 --> 00:04:35.930
can do what only governments
and corporations used

00:04:35.930 --> 00:04:37.610
to do mere decades ago.

00:04:37.610 --> 00:04:41.226
The tools to change the world
are in everybody's hands.

00:04:41.226 --> 00:04:42.750
I think that's a wonderful idea.

00:04:42.750 --> 00:04:44.500
Because on the back
of these exponentials,

00:04:44.500 --> 00:04:46.890
you are now more empowered
than you've ever been.

00:04:46.890 --> 00:04:49.385
So again, the question is,
what is your contribution

00:04:49.385 --> 00:04:50.100
going to be?

