00:22:51.729 --> 00:22:52.520
It looks beautiful.

00:22:52.520 --> 00:22:55.320
Jacque Fresco,
definitely a smart guy.

00:22:55.320 --> 00:22:56.070
I think it's cool.

00:22:56.070 --> 00:22:59.910
I think all possible
Utopian visions

00:22:59.910 --> 00:23:03.630
are worth investigating and
pursuing in some capacity.

00:23:03.630 --> 00:23:07.620
Just the idea of us trying to
create perfection turns me on.

00:23:11.596 --> 00:23:13.010
"The future is already here.

00:23:13.010 --> 00:23:14.840
It's just unevenly distributed."

00:23:14.840 --> 00:23:15.340
Yeah.

00:23:15.340 --> 00:23:16.670
People talk about
this all the time.

00:23:16.670 --> 00:23:18.710
They say, yeah, these
technologies sound great.

00:23:18.710 --> 00:23:20.290
But what about the info-nots?

00:23:20.290 --> 00:23:23.230
You have the info-haves,
and you have the info-nots.

00:23:23.230 --> 00:23:24.860
Kurzweil answered
this brilliantly.

00:23:24.860 --> 00:23:28.079
He says, people are afraid
these technologies are only

00:23:28.079 --> 00:23:28.620
for the rich.

00:23:28.620 --> 00:23:31.640
And he answers, yeah,
like cellphones, right?

00:23:31.640 --> 00:23:33.140
When cell phones
were first created,

00:23:33.140 --> 00:23:35.264
they were expensive, clunky,
didn't work very well,

00:23:35.264 --> 00:23:37.540
and perhaps only a
few could afford them.

00:23:37.540 --> 00:23:39.540
Today, a young person
with a cellphone in Africa

00:23:39.540 --> 00:23:41.540
has better communications
technology than the US

00:23:41.540 --> 00:23:42.902
president had 25 years ago.

00:23:42.902 --> 00:23:44.985
So these technologies,
they improve exponentially.

00:23:44.985 --> 00:23:47.080
They get cheaper, they
get more accessible,

00:23:47.080 --> 00:23:48.817
and they get more affordable.

00:23:48.817 --> 00:23:50.650
So I don't think these
technologies are just

00:23:50.650 --> 00:23:51.700
for the rich at all.

00:23:51.700 --> 00:23:54.780
I think they spread and they
become available to everyone.

00:23:58.650 --> 00:24:00.560
"What is your take on
vibrational [? seet ?]

00:24:00.560 --> 00:24:04.990
frequency, multiverses,
ascension?"

00:24:04.990 --> 00:24:07.960
I can't speak too much
about any of those other

00:24:07.960 --> 00:24:11.300
than the multiverse idea.

00:24:11.300 --> 00:24:14.280
The parallel universe
theory of quantum mechanics

00:24:14.280 --> 00:24:16.430
that was proposed
by Hugh Everett III

00:24:16.430 --> 00:24:19.880
is this idea that the only
way to explain quantum physics

00:24:19.880 --> 00:24:23.170
is to assume that every possible
thing that could ever possibly

00:24:23.170 --> 00:24:26.592
happen is happening in some kind
of parallel universe to ours.

00:24:26.592 --> 00:24:28.300
There was a great book
called The Man who

00:24:28.300 --> 00:24:30.980
Turned into Himself,
which took that idea

00:24:30.980 --> 00:24:33.430
and wrote a fictional
account of it.

00:24:33.430 --> 00:24:36.110
This guy, his wife dies, and
he just can't bear the pain.

00:24:36.110 --> 00:24:38.745
And somehow, he learns to surf
between parallel universes.

00:24:38.745 --> 00:24:40.870
And he ends up going to
the other parallel universe

00:24:40.870 --> 00:24:44.030
in which his wife didn't die,
and then gets to be with her.

00:24:44.030 --> 00:24:45.370
It's an amazing story.

00:24:45.370 --> 00:24:47.880
Also, Michael
Crichton's book Timeline

00:24:47.880 --> 00:24:50.390
use the parallel universe
theory of quantum mechanics

00:24:50.390 --> 00:24:51.610
to achieve time travel.

00:24:51.610 --> 00:24:55.050
Because obviously, I can't go
to the past of this universe,

00:24:55.050 --> 00:24:58.880
but I can go to a parallel
universe in which their present

00:24:58.880 --> 00:25:01.970
looks a lot like what
our past looked like.

00:25:01.970 --> 00:25:04.360
And in order to get to
that parallel universe,

00:25:04.360 --> 00:25:06.750
you can't fit human
through a wormhole.

00:25:06.750 --> 00:25:08.459
But you can send a fax.

00:25:08.459 --> 00:25:10.250
The same way you can't
put a piece of paper

00:25:10.250 --> 00:25:12.420
through a telephone line,
but you can send a fax.

00:25:12.420 --> 00:25:14.990
So they figure out how to scan
the information equivalent

00:25:14.990 --> 00:25:16.970
of the human being,
destroy the human

00:25:16.970 --> 00:25:19.076
on this side at the same
time as they zap you

00:25:19.076 --> 00:25:19.950
through the wormhole.

00:25:19.950 --> 00:25:22.160
And then the other
universe reconstructs you

00:25:22.160 --> 00:25:24.930
upon receiving your
particles, somehow.

00:25:24.930 --> 00:25:27.480
You self-organize, and you
just pop out the other side.

00:25:27.480 --> 00:25:29.730
It's an idea, but
kind of a wild idea.

00:25:29.730 --> 00:25:31.710
But Michael Crichton
in Timeline explored it

00:25:31.710 --> 00:25:33.422
in a pretty cool way.

00:25:33.422 --> 00:25:36.530
I can't believe I
actually remembered that.

00:25:36.530 --> 00:25:37.320
How are we doing?

