00:28:44.043 --> 00:28:46.794
Yes, Well, comedians are the
original stand-up philosophers.

00:28:46.794 --> 00:28:48.960
Or at least, the contemporary
stand-up philosophers.

00:28:48.960 --> 00:28:50.490
There's not a lot of
spaces today outside

00:28:50.490 --> 00:28:52.710
of university campuses
where somebody can stand up

00:28:52.710 --> 00:28:55.280
and pontificate on things.

00:28:55.280 --> 00:28:57.260
I try to do it in my talks.

00:28:57.260 --> 00:29:03.500
But comics like Joe Rogan, like
George Carlin, like Bill Maher,

00:29:03.500 --> 00:29:05.470
these are contemporary
philosophers.

00:29:05.470 --> 00:29:07.520
They get up on stage
and they think out loud.

00:29:07.520 --> 00:29:09.690
And they ruminate with you.

00:29:09.690 --> 00:29:12.320
And they share anecdotes
and make observations

00:29:12.320 --> 00:29:13.190
about the world.

00:29:13.190 --> 00:29:14.616
They philosophize.

00:29:14.616 --> 00:29:16.240
And then they have
this humorous twist.

00:29:16.240 --> 00:29:18.610
We laugh because we
relate to what they're

00:29:18.610 --> 00:29:21.850
saying, because they
mirror us brilliantly.

00:29:21.850 --> 00:29:23.450
So I definitely
think that comedians

00:29:23.450 --> 00:29:25.410
are contemporary
stand-up philosophers.

00:29:31.980 --> 00:29:33.650
Technology, extension
of ourselves,

00:29:33.650 --> 00:29:35.560
reflection of ourselves,
our true potential.

00:29:35.560 --> 00:29:38.300
